# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: current-sensing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] An **ammeter** (abbreviation of *ampere meter*) is an instrument used to measure the current in a circuit.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Electric currents are measured in amperes (A), hence the name.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] For direct measurement, the ammeter is connected in series with the circuit in which the current is to be measured.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] An ammeter usually has low resistance so that it does not cause a significant voltage drop in the circuit being measured.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Instruments used to measure smaller currents, in the milliampere or microampere range, are designated as *milliammeters* or *microammeters*.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Early ammeters were laboratory instruments that relied on the Earth's magnetic field for operation.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] By the late 19th century, improved instruments were designed which could be mounted in any position and allowed accurate measurements in electric power systems.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] It is generally represented by letter 'A' in a circuit.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The relation between electric current, magnetic fields and physical forces was first noted by Hans Christian Ørsted in 1820, who observed a compass needle was deflected from pointing North when a current flowed in an adjacent wire.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The tangent galvanometer was used to measure currents using this effect, where the restoring force returning the pointer to the zero position was provided by the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] This made these instruments usable only when aligned with the Earth's field.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Sensitivity of the instrument was increased by using additional turns of wire to multiply the effect – the instruments were called "multipliers".
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The word *rheoscope* as a detector of electrical currents was coined by Sir Charles Wheatstone about 1840 but is no longer used to describe electrical instruments.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The word makeup is similar to that of *rheostat* (also coined by Wheatstone) which was a device used to adjust the current in a circuit.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Rheostat is a historical term for a variable resistance, though unlike rheoscope may still be encountered.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Some instruments are *panel meters*, meant to be mounted on some sort of control panel.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Of these, the flat, horizontal or vertical type is often called an *edgewise meter*.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The D'Arsonval galvanometer is a moving coil ammeter.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] It uses magnetic deflection, where current passing through a coil placed in the magnetic field of a permanent magnet causes the coil to move.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The modern form of this instrument was developed by Edward Weston, and uses two spiral springs to provide the restoring force.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The uniform air gap between the iron core and the permanent magnet poles make the deflection of the meter linearly proportional to current.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Basic meter movements can have full-scale deflection for currents from about 25 microamperes to 10 milliamperes.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Because the magnetic field is polarised, the meter needle acts in opposite directions for each direction of current.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] A DC ammeter is thus sensitive to which polarity it is connected in; most are marked with a positive terminal, but some have centre-zero mechanisms and can display currents in either direction.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] A moving coil meter indicates the average (mean) of a varying current through it, which is zero for AC.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] For this reason, moving-coil meters are only usable directly for DC, not AC.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] This type of meter movement is extremely common for both ammeters and other meters derived from them, such as voltmeters and ohmmeters.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Moving magnet ammeters operate on essentially the same principle as moving coil, except that the coil is mounted in the meter case, and a permanent magnet moves the needle.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Moving magnet Ammeters are able to carry larger currents than moving coil instruments, often several tens of amperes, because the coil can be made of thicker wire and the current does not have to be carried by the hairsprings.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Indeed, some Ammeters of this type do not have hairsprings at all, instead using a fixed permanent magnet to provide the restoring force.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] An electrodynamic ammeter uses an electromagnet instead of the permanent magnet of the d'Arsonval movement.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] This instrument can respond to both alternating and direct current and also indicates true RMS for AC.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] See wattmeter for an alternative use for this instrument.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Moving iron ammeters use a piece of iron which moves when acted upon by the electromagnetic force of a fixed coil of wire.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The moving-iron meter was invented by Austrian engineer Friedrich Drexler in 1884.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] This type of meter responds to both direct and alternating currents (as opposed to the moving-coil ammeter, which works on direct current only).
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The iron element consists of a moving vane attached to a pointer, and a fixed vane, surrounded by a coil.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] As alternating or direct current flows through the coil and induces a magnetic field in both vanes, the vanes repel each other and the moving vane deflects against the restoring force provided by fine helical springs.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The deflection of a moving iron meter is proportional to the square of the current.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Consequently, such meters would normally have a nonlinear scale, but the iron parts are usually modified in shape to make the scale fairly linear over most of its range.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Moving iron instruments indicate the RMS value of any AC waveform applied.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Moving iron ammeters are commonly used to measure current in industrial frequency AC circuits.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] In a hot-wire ammeter, a current passes through a wire which expands as it heats.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Although these instruments have slow response time and low accuracy, they were sometimes used in measuring radio-frequency current.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] These also measure true RMS for an applied AC.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] In much the same way as the analogue ammeter formed the basis for a wide variety of derived meters, including voltmeters, the basic mechanism for a digital meter is a digital voltmeter mechanism, and other types of meter are built around this.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Digital ammeter designs use a shunt resistor to produce a calibrated voltage proportional to the current flowing.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] This voltage is then measured by a digital voltmeter, through use of an analog-to-digital converter (ADC); the digital display is calibrated to display the current through the shunt.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Such instruments are often calibrated to indicate the RMS value for a sine wave only, but many designs will indicate true RMS within limitations of the wave crest factor.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] There is also a range of devices referred to as integrating ammeters.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] In these ammeters the current is summed over time, giving as a result the product of current and time; which is proportional to the electrical charge transferred with that current.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] These can be used for metering energy (the charge needs to be multiplied by the voltage to give energy) or for estimating the charge of a battery or capacitor.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] A picoammeter, or pico ammeter, measures very low electric current, usually from the picoampere range at the lower end to the milliampere range at the upper end.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Picoammeters are used where the current being measured is below the limits of sensitivity of other devices, such as multimeters.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Most picoammeters use a "virtual short" technique and have several different measurement ranges that must be switched between to cover multiple decades of measurement.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Other modern picoammeters use log compression and a "current sink" method that eliminates range switching and associated voltage spikes.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Special design and usage considerations must be observed in order to reduce leakage current which may swamp measurements such as special insulators and driven shields.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Triaxial cable is often used for probe connections.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Ammeters must be connected in series with the circuit to be measured.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] For relatively small currents (up to a few amperes), an ammeter may pass the whole of the circuit current.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] For larger direct currents, a shunt resistor carries most of the circuit current and a small, accurately-known fraction of the current passes through the meter movement.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] For alternating current circuits, a current transformer may be used to provide a convenient small current to drive an instrument, such as 1 or 5 amperes, while the primary current to be measured is much larger (up to thousands of amperes).
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The use of a shunt or current transformer also allows convenient location of the indicating meter without the need to run heavy circuit conductors up to the point of observation.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] In the case of alternating current, the use of a current transformer also isolates the meter from the high voltage of the primary circuit.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] A shunt provides no such isolation for a direct-current ammeter, but where high voltages are used it may be possible to place the ammeter in the "return" side of the circuit which may be at low potential with respect to earth.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Ammeters must not be connected directly across a voltage source since their internal resistance is very low and excess current would flow.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Ammeters are designed for a low voltage drop across their terminals, much less than one volt; the extra circuit losses produced by the ammeter are called its "burden" on the measured circuit(I).
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Ordinary Weston-type meter movements can measure only milliamperes at most, because the springs and practical coils can carry only limited currents.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] To measure larger currents, a resistor called a *shunt* is placed in parallel with the meter.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The resistances of shunts is in the integer to fractional milliohm range.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Nearly all of the current flows through the shunt, and only a small fraction flows through the meter.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] This allows the meter to measure large currents.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Traditionally, the meter used with a shunt has a full-scale deflection (FSD) of 50 mV, so shunts are typically designed to produce a voltage drop of 50 mV when carrying their full rated current.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] To make a multi-range ammeter, a selector switch can be used to connect one of a number of shunts across the meter.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] It must be a make-before-break switch to avoid damaging current surges through the meter movement when switching ranges.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] A better arrangement is the Ayrton shunt or universal shunt, invented by William E.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Ayrton, which does not require a make-before-break switch.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] It also avoids any inaccuracy because of contact resistance.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] In the figure, assuming for example, a movement with a full-scale voltage of 50 mV and desired current ranges of 10 mA, 100 mA, and 1 A, the resistance values would be: R1 = 4.5 ohms, R2 = 0.45 ohm, R3 = 0.05 ohm.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] And if the movement resistance is 1000 ohms, for example, R1 must be adjusted to 4.525 ohms.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Switched shunts are rarely used for currents above 10 amperes.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Zero-center ammeters are used for applications requiring current to be measured with both polarities, common in scientific and industrial equipment.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Zero-center ammeters are also commonly placed in series with a battery.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] In this application, the charging of the battery deflects the needle to one side of the scale (commonly, the right side) and the discharging of the battery deflects the needle to the other side.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] A special type of zero-center ammeter for testing high currents in cars and trucks has a pivoted bar magnet that moves the pointer, and a fixed bar magnet to keep the pointer centered with no current.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] The magnetic field around the wire carrying current to be measured deflects the moving magnet.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Since the ammeter shunt has a very low resistance, mistakenly wiring the ammeter in parallel with a voltage source will cause a short circuit, at best blowing a fuse, possibly damaging the instrument and wiring, and exposing an observer to injury.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] In AC circuits, a current transformer can be used to convert the large current in the main circuit into a smaller current more suited to a meter.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Some designs of transformer are able to directly convert the magnetic field around a conductor into a small AC current, typically either 1 A or 5 A at full rated current, that can be easily read by a meter.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] In a similar way, accurate AC/DC non-contact ammeters have been constructed using Hall effect magnetic field sensors.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] A portable hand-held clamp-on ammeter is a common tool for maintenance of industrial and commercial electrical equipment, which is temporarily clipped over a wire to measure current.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Some recent types have a parallel pair of magnetically soft probes that are placed on either side of the conductor.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] In particle accelerators and synchrotron light sources, ammeters with extremely high sensitivity, known as **picoammeters**, are used to measure the tiny currents generated by photodiodes and other beam position monitors (BPMs).
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] These instruments typically provide multiple low-noise input channels with femtoampere to microampere sensitivity, enabling real-time determination of the photon beam position and intensity.
[src:current-sensing/ammeter] Such devices are crucial for beam stabilization and feedback systems in facilities like the Advanced Photon Source at Argonne National Laboratory, where custom picoammeters are employed to ensure precise orbit control and improved beamline performance.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] In electrical and electronic engineering, a **current clamp**, also known as **current probe**, is an electrical device with jaws which open to allow clamping around an electrical conductor.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] This allows measurement of the current in a conductor without the need to make physical contact with it, or to disconnect it for insertion through the probe.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Current clamps are typically used to read the magnitude of alternating current (AC) and, with additional instrumentation, the phase and waveform can also be measured.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Some clamp meters can measure currents of 1000 A and more.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Hall effect and vane type clamps can also measure direct current (DC).
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The Hall effect type is more sensitive and is able to measure both DC and AC, in some applications, up to the kilohertz range.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] This type was initially used with oscilloscopes, and with high-end computerized digital multimeters, however, they have become commonplace for general use.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] A common form of AC current clamp comprises a split ring made of ferrite or soft iron.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] A wire coil is wound round one or both halves, forming one winding of a current transformer.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The conductor it is clamped around forms the other winding.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Like any transformer this type works only with AC or pulse waveforms, with some examples extending into the megahertz range.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] When measuring current, the subject conductor forms the primary winding and the coil forms the secondary.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] This type may also be used in reverse, to inject current into the conductor, for example in electromagnetic compatibility susceptibility testing to induce an interference current.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Usually, the injection probe is specifically designed for this purpose.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] In this mode, the coil forms the primary and the test conductor the secondary.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] In the iron vane type, the magnetic flux in the core directly affects a moving iron vane, allowing both AC and DC to be measured, and gives a true root mean square (RMS) value for non-sinusoidal AC waveforms.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Due to its physical size it is generally limited to power transmission frequencies up to around 100 Hz.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The vane is usually fixed directly to the display mechanism of an analogue (moving pointer) clamp meter.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The calibration of the instrument is clearly non-linear.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Resembling a current clamp in appearance and function is the Rogowski coil current sensor.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] This coreless transformer is used in clamp meters and power monitoring loggers.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] It has the advantage of better linearity, having no core to saturate, it can be made flexible, and does not require any magnetic or electrical contact at the opening end.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The Rogowski coil gives a voltage proportional to the rate of change of current in the primary cable, so more signal processing is needed before the sensed values can be displayed.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] An electrical meter with integral AC current clamp is known as a clamp meter, clamp-on ammeter, tong tester, or colloquially as an amp clamp.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] A clamp meter measures the vector sum of the currents flowing in all the conductors passing through the probe, which depends on the phase relationship of the currents.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Only one conductor is normally passed through the probe.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] In particular if the clamp is closed around a two-conductor cable carrying power to equipment, the same current flows down one conductor and up the other; the meter correctly reads a net current of zero.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] As electrical cables for equipment have both insulated conductors (and possibly an earth wire) bonded together, clamp meters are often used with what is essentially a short extension cord with the two conductors separated, so that the clamp can be placed around only one conductor of this extension.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] A relatively recent development is a multi-conductor clamp meter with several sensor coils around the jaws of the clamp.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] This could be clamped around standard two- or three-conductor single-phase cables to provide a readout of the current flowing through the load, with no need to separate the conductors.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The reading produced by a conductor carrying a very low current can be increased by winding the conductor around the clamp several times; the meter reading divided by the number of turns is the current, with some loss of accuracy due to inductive effects.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Clamp meters are used by electricians, sometimes with the clamp incorporated into a general purpose multimeter.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] It is simple to measure very high currents (hundreds of amperes) with the appropriate current transformer.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Accurate measurement of low currents (a few milliamperes) with a current transformer clamp is more difficult.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The range of any given meter can be extended by passing the conductor through the jaw multiple times.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] For example a 0–200 A meter can be turned into a 0–20 A meter by winding the conductor 10 times around the jaw's core.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Less-expensive clamp meters use a rectifier circuit which actually reads mean current, but is calibrated to display the RMS current corresponding to the measured mean, giving a correct RMS reading only if the current is a sine wave.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] For other waveforms readings will be incorrect; when these simpler meters are used with non-sinusoidal loads such as the ballasts used with fluorescent lamps or high-intensity discharge lamps or most modern computer and electronic equipment, readings can be quite inaccurate.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Meters which respond to true RMS rather than mean current are described as "true RMS".
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Typical hand-held Hall effect units can read currents as low as 200 mA, and units that can read down to 1 mA are available.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The Columbia tong test ammeter (illustrated) is an example of the iron vane type, used for measuring large AC currents up to 1000 amperes.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The iron jaws of the meter direct the magnetic field surrounding the conductor to an iron vane that is attached to the needle of the meter.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The iron vane moves in proportion to the strength of the magnetic field, and thus produces a meter indication proportional to the current.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] This type of ammeter can measure both AC and DC currents and provides a true RMS current measurement of non-sinusoidal or distorted AC waveforms.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Interchangeable meter movements can be installed in the clamping assembly to provide various full-scale current values up to 1000 amperes.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The iron vane is in a small cylinder that is inserted in a space at the hinged end of the clamp-on jaws.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Several jaw sizes are available for clamping around large conductors and bus bars up to 4+1⁄2 inches (110 mm) wide.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] As the illustration shows, the scale is very non-linear and unsuitable for measuring low currents, with currents of less than half the full-scale deflection crammed into a short section of the dial.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Clamp probes are used with some meters to measure electrical power and energy.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] The clamp measures the current and other circuitry the voltage; the true power is the product of the instantaneous voltage and current integrated over a cycle.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] Comprehensive meters designed to measure many parameters of electrical energy (power factor, distortion, instantaneous power as a function of time, phase relationships, etc.), use this principle.
[src:current-sensing/current-clamp] A single clamp is used for single-phase measurements; with an appropriate instrument with three clamps, measurements may be made on three-phase power systems.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] In electrical engineering, **current sensing** is any one of several techniques used to measure electric current.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The measurement of current ranges from picoamps to tens of thousands of amperes.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The selection of a current sensing method depends on requirements such as magnitude, accuracy, bandwidth, robustness, cost, isolation or size.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The current value may be directly displayed by an instrument, or converted to digital form for use by a monitoring or control system.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Current sensing techniques include shunt resistor, current transformers and Rogowski coils, magnetic-field based transducers and others.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] A current sensor is a device that detects electric current in a wire and generates a signal proportional to that current.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The generated signal could be analog voltage or current or a digital output.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The generated signal can be then used to display the measured current in an ammeter, or can be stored for further analysis in a data acquisition system, or can be used for the purpose of control.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Current sensing technologies must fulfill various requirements, for various applications.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Ohm's law is the observation that the voltage drop across a resistor is proportional to the current going through it.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] This relationship can be used to sense currents.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Sensors based on this simple relationship are well known for their lower costs, and reliability due to this simple principle.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The common and simple approach to current sensing is the use of a shunt resistor.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] That the voltage drop across the shunt is proportional to its current flow, i.e. ohm's law, makes the low resistance current shunt a very popular choice for current measurement system with its low cost and high reliability.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Both alternating currents (AC) and direct currents (DC) can be measured with the shunt resistor.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The high performance coaxial shunt have been widely used for many applications fast rise-time transient currents and high amplitudes but, highly integrated electronic devices prefer low-cost surface mounted devices (SMDs), because of their small sizes and relatively low prices.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The parasitic inductance present in the shunt affects high precision current measurement.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Although this affects only the magnitude of the impedance at relatively high frequency, but also its effect on the phase at line frequency causes a noticeable error at a low power factor.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The major disadvantage of using the shunt is that fundamentally a shunt is a resistive element, the power loss is thus proportional to the square of the current passing through it and consequently it is a rarity amongst high current measurements.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Fast-response for measuring high-impulse or heavy-surge currents is the common requirement for shunt resistors.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] In 1981 Malewski, designed a circuit to eliminate the skin effect and later in 1999 the flat-strap sandwich shunt (FSSS) was introduced from a flat-strap sandwich resistor.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The properties of the FSSS in terms of response time, power loss and frequency characteristics, are the same as the shunt resistor but the cost is lower and the construction technique is less sophisticated, compared to Malewski and the coaxial shunt.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The intrinsic resistance of a conducting element, such as a copper trace on a printed circuit board can be used as a sensing resistor.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The voltage drop of a copper trace is very low due to its very low resistance, making the presence of a high gain amplifier mandatory in order to get a useful signal.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Accuracy is limited by the initial tolerance of manufacturing the trace and the significant temperature coefficient of copper.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] A digital controller may apply corrections to improve the measurement.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] A significant drawback of a resistor sensor is the unavoidable electrical connection between the current to be measured and the measurement circuit.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] An isolation amplifier can provide electrical isolation between measured current and the rest of the measurement circuit.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] However, these amplifiers are expensive and can also limit the bandwidth, accuracy and thermal drift of the original current sensing technique.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Other current sensing techniques that provide intrinsic electrical isolation may deliver a sufficient performance at lower costs where isolation is required.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Faraday's Law of induction – that states: the total electromotive force induced in a closed circuit is proportional to the time rate of change of the total magnetic flux linking the circuit – has been largely employed in current sensing techniques.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Two major sensing devices based on Faraday’s law are Current transformers (CTs) and Rogowski coils.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] These sensors provide an intrinsic electrical isolation between the current to be measured and the output signal, thus making these current sensing devices mandatory, where safety standards demand electrical isolation.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The CT is based on the principle of a transformer and converts a high primary current into a smaller secondary current and is common among high AC current measurement system.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] As this device is a passive device, no extra driving circuitry is needed in its implementation.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Another major advantage is that it can measure very high current while consuming little power.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The disadvantage of the CT is that a very high primary current or a substantial DC component in the current can saturate the ferrite material used in the core ultimately corrupting the signal.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Another problem is that once the core is magnetized, it will contain hysteresis and the accuracy will degrade unless it is demagnetized again.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Rogowski coil is based on Faraday’s law of induction and the output voltage Vout of the Rogowski coil is determined by integrating the current Ic to be measured.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] where A is the cross-sectional area of the coil and N is the number of turns.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The Rogowski coil has a low sensitivity due to the absence of a high permeability magnetic core that the current transformer can take advantage of.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] However, this can be compensated for by adding more turns on the Rogowski coil or using an integrator with a higher gain k.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] More turns increase the self-capacitance and self-inductance, and higher integrator gain means an amplifier with a large gain-bandwidth product.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] As always in engineering, trade-offs must be made depending on specific applications.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Hall effect sensors are devices based on the Hall-effect, which was discovered by Edwin Hall in 1879 based on the physical principle of the Lorentz force.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] They are activated by an external magnetic field.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] In this generalized device, the Hall sensor senses the magnetic field produced by the magnetic system.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] This system responds to the quantity to be sensed (current, temperature, position, velocity, etc.) through the input interface.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The Hall element is the basic magnetic field sensor.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] It requires signal conditioning to make the output usable for most applications.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The signal conditioning electronics needed are an amplifier stage and temperature compensation.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Voltage regulation is needed when operating from an unregulated supply.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] If the Hall voltage is measured when no magnetic field is present, the output should be zero.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] However, if voltage at each output terminal is measured with respect to ground, a non-zero voltage will appear.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] This is the common mode voltage (CMV), and is the same at each output terminal.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The output interface then converts the electrical signal from the Hall sensor; the Hall voltage: a signal that is significant to the application context.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The Hall voltage is a low level signal on the order of 30 μvolts in the presence of one gauss magnetic field.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] This low-level output requires an amplifier with low noise, high input impedance and moderate gain.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] A differential amplifier with these characteristics can be readily integrated with the Hall element using standard bipolar transistor technology.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Temperature compensation is also easily integrated.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] This range of current sensors is based on the principle that whenever a current flows in a conduct a magnetic field is produced around the conductor with a strength directly proportional to the magnitude of that current flowing.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] A Hall-effect magnetic field sensor is then used to measure the induced current with its output being directly proportional to the magnitude of the current flowing.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] In the simplest configuration, a Hall-effect magnetic field sensor can be placed adjacent to the conductor and its output measured but there are limitations.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] For current levels under about 10 amps, the magnetic field produced is very weak and not a lot stronger than the earth's magnetic field.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Also the Hall voltage produced will be tiny so very high amplification would be required with its associated thermal instability and noise issues.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Fluxgate sensors or saturable inductor current sensors work on the same measurement principle as Hall-effect-based current sensors: the magnetic field created by the primary current to be measured is detected by a specific sensing element.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The design of the saturable inductor current sensor is similar to that of a closed-loop Hall-effect current sensor; the only difference is that this method uses the saturable inductor instead of the Hall-effect sensor in the air gap.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Saturable inductor current sensor is based on the detection of an inductance change.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The saturable inductor is made of small and thin magnetic core wound with a coil around it.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The saturable inductor operates into its saturation region.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] It is designed in such a way that the external and internal flux density will affect its saturation level.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Change in the saturation level of a saturable inductor will alter core’s permeability and, consequently, its inductance L.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] The value of saturable inductance (L) is high at low currents (based on the permeability of the core) and low at high currents (the core permeability becomes unity when saturated).
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] When interpretating Fluxgate detectors, it needs to consider the property of many magnetic materials to exhibit a non-linear relationship between the magnetic field strength H and the flux density B.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] In this technique, high frequency performance is achieved by using two cores without air gaps.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] One of the two main cores is used to create a saturable inductor and the other is used to create a high frequency transformer effect.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] In another approach, three cores can be used without air gap.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Two of the three cores are used to create saturable inductor, and the third core is used to create a high frequency transformer effect.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Advantages of saturable inductor sensors include high resolution, high accuracy, low offset and gain drift, and large bandwidth (up to 500 kHz).
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Drawbacks of saturable inductor technologies include limited bandwidth for simpler design, relatively high secondary power consumption, and risk of current or voltage noise injection into the primary conductor.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] A widely used implementation of fluxgate technology for precision current measurement is the *Direct Current Current Transformer* (DCCT), also called zero-flux DCCT.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] This principle was first introduced at CERN in the 1960s and is today considered the state-of-the-art method for high-accuracy current sensing.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] A magneto-resistor (MR) is a two terminal device which changes its resistance parabolically with applied magnetic field.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] This variation of the resistance of MR due to the magnetic field is known as the Magnetoresistive Effect.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] It is possible to build structures in which the electrical resistance varies as a function of applied magnetic field.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] These structures can be used as magnetic sensors.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Normally these resistors are assembled in a bridge configuration to compensate for thermal drift.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Popular magneto resistance-based sensors are: Anisotropic Magneto Resistance (AMR), Giant Magneto Resistance (GMR), Giant Magneto Impendence (GMI) and Tunnel Magneto Resistance (TMR).
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] All these MR-based sensors have higher sensitivity compared to Hall-effect sensors.
[src:current-sensing/current-sensor] Despite this, these sensors (GMR, CMR, and TMR) are still more expensive than Hall-effect devices, have serious drawbacks related with nonlinear behavior, distinct thermal drift, and a very strong external field can permanently alter the sensor behavior (GMR).
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] A **current transformer** (**CT**) is a type of transformer that reduces or multiplies alternating current (AC), producing a current in its secondary which is proportional to the current in its primary.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers, along with voltage or potential transformers, are instrument transformers, which scale the large values of voltage or current to small, standardized values that are easy to handle for measuring instruments and protective relays.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Instrument transformers isolate measurement or protection circuits from the high voltage of the primary system.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] A current transformer presents a negligible load to the primary circuit.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers are the current-sensing units of the power system and are used at generating stations, electrical substations, and in industrial and commercial electric power distribution.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] A current transformer has a primary winding, a core, and a secondary winding, although some transformers use an air core.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] While the physical principles are the same, the details of a "current" transformer compared with a "voltage" transformer differ because of different requirements of the application.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] A current transformer is designed to maintain an accurate ratio between the currents in its primary and secondary circuits over a defined range.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The alternating current in the primary produces an alternating magnetic field in the core, which then induces an alternating current in the secondary.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The primary circuit is largely unaffected by the insertion of the CT.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Accurate current transformers need close coupling between the primary and secondary to ensure that the secondary current is proportional to the primary current over a wide current range.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The current in the secondary is the current in the primary (assuming a single turn primary) divided by the number of turns of the secondary.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] In the illustration on the right, 'I' is the current in the primary, 'B' is the magnetic field, 'N' is the number of turns on the secondary, and 'A' is an AC ammeter.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers typically consist of a silicon steel ring core wound with many turns of copper wire, as shown in the illustration to the right.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The conductor carrying the primary current is passed through the ring.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The CT's primary, therefore, consists of a single 'turn'.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The primary 'winding' may be a permanent part of the current transformer, i.e., a heavy copper bar to carry current through the core.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Window-type (toroidal) current transformers are also common, which can have circuit cables run through the center of the core to provide a single-turn primary winding.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] To assist accuracy, the primary conductor should be centered in the aperture.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] CTs are specified by their current ratio from primary to secondary.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The rated secondary current is normally standardized at 1 or 5 amperes.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] For example, a 4000:5 CT secondary winding will supply an output current of 5 amperes when the primary winding current is 4000 amperes.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] This ratio can also be used to find the impedance or voltage on one side of the transformer, given the appropriate value at the other side.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] For the 4000:5 CT, the secondary impedance can be found as ZS = NZP = 800ZP, and the secondary voltage can be found as VS = NVP = 800VP.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] In some cases, the secondary impedance is *referred* to the primary side, and is found as ZS′ = N2ZP.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Referring the impedance is done simply by multiplying initial secondary impedance value by the current ratio.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The secondary winding of a CT can have taps to provide a range of ratios, five taps being common.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformer shapes and sizes vary depending on the end-user or switch gear manufacturer.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Low-voltage single ratio metering current transformers are either a ring type or plastic molded case.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Split-core current transformers either have a two-part core or a core with a removable section.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] This allows the transformer to be placed around a conductor without disconnecting it first.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Split-core current transformers are typically used in low current measuring instruments, often portable, battery-operated, and hand-held (see illustration lower right).
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers are used extensively for measuring current and monitoring the operation of the power grid.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Along with voltage leads, revenue-grade CTs drive the electrical utility's watt-hour meter on many larger commercial and industrial supplies.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] High-voltage current transformers are mounted on porcelain or polymer insulators to isolate them from ground.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Some CT configurations slip around the bushing of a high-voltage transformer or circuit breaker, which automatically centers the conductor inside the CT window.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers can be mounted on the low voltage or high voltage leads of a power transformer.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Sometimes a section of a bus bar can be removed to replace a current transformer.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Often, multiple CTs are installed as a "stack" for various uses.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] For example, protection devices and revenue metering may use separate CTs to provide isolation between metering and protection circuits and allows current transformers with different characteristics (accuracy, overload performance) to be used for the devices.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] In the United States, the National Electrical Code (NEC) requires residual current devices in commercial and residential electrical systems to protect outlets installed in "wet" locations such as kitchens and bathrooms, as well as weatherproof outlets installed outdoors.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Such devices, most commonly **ground fault circuit interrupters** (GFCIs), typically run both the 120-volt energized conductor and the neutral return conductor through a current transformer, with the secondary coil connected to a trip device.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Under normal conditions, the current in the two circuit wires will be equal and flow in opposite directions, resulting in zero net current through the CT and no current in the secondary coil.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] This net current flow will induce current in the secondary coil, which will cause the trip device to operate and de-energize the circuit - typically within 0.2 seconds.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The burden (load) impedance should not exceed the specified maximum value to avoid the secondary voltage exceeding the limits for the current transformer.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The primary current rating of a current transformer should not be exceeded, or the core may enter its non-linear region and ultimately saturate.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] This would occur near the end of the first half of each half (positive and negative) of the AC sine wave in the primary and compromise accuracy.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers are often used to monitor high currents or currents at high voltages.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Technical standards and design practices are used to ensure the safety of installations using current transformers.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The secondary of a current transformer should not be disconnected from its burden while current is in the primary, as the secondary will attempt to continue driving current into an effective infinite impedance potentially generating high voltages and thus compromising operator safety.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] For certain current transformers, this voltage may reach several kilovolts and may cause arcing.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Exceeding the secondary voltage may also degrade the accuracy of the transformer or destroy it.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Output voltage is limited by core saturation since the primary flux is not canceled by secondary flux when the core is saturated.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Because of this, smaller current transformers may not actually incur dangerous voltages when operating nominally.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Faster current transients from loads being switched on etc. can however still induce dangerous voltage levels due to high current slope.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Accuracy classes for various types of measurement and at standard loads in the secondary circuit (burdens) are defined in IEC 61869-1 as classes 0.1, 0.2s, 0.2, 0.5, 0.5s, 1 and 3.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The class designation is an approximate measure of the CT's accuracy.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The ratio (primary to secondary current) error of a Class 1 CT is 1% at rated current; the ratio error of a Class 0.5 CT is 0.5% or less.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Errors in phase are also important, especially in power measuring circuits.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Each class has an allowable maximum phase error for a specified load impedance.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers used for protective relaying also have accuracy requirements at overload currents in excess of the normal rating to ensure accurate performance of relays during system faults.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] A CT with a rating of 2.5L400 specifies with an output from its secondary winding of twenty times its rated secondary current (usually 5 A × 20 = 100 A) and 400 V (IZ drop) its output accuracy will be within 2.5 percent.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The secondary load of a current transformer is termed the "burden" to distinguish it from the primary load.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The burden in a CT metering electrical network is largely resistive impedance presented to its secondary winding.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Typical burden ratings for IEC CTs are 1.5 VA, 3 VA, 5 VA, 10 VA, 15 VA, 20 VA, 30 VA, 45 VA and 60 VA.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] This means a CT with a burden rating of B-0.2 will maintain its stated accuracy with up to 0.2 Ω on the secondary circuit.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] These specification diagrams show accuracy parallelograms on a grid incorporating magnitude and phase angle error scales at the CT's rated burden.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Items that contribute to the burden of a current measurement circuit are switch-blocks, meters and intermediate conductors.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The most common cause of excess burden impedance is the conductor between the meter and the CT.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] When substation meters are located far from the meter cabinets, the excessive length of cable creates a large resistance.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] This problem can be reduced by using thicker cables and CTs with lower secondary currents (1 A), both of which will produce less voltage drop between the CT and its metering devices.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The **knee-point voltage** of a current transformer is the magnitude of the secondary voltage above which the output current ceases to linearly follow the input current within declared accuracy.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] In testing, if a voltage is applied across the secondary terminals the magnetizing current will increase in proportion to the applied voltage, until the knee point is reached.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The knee point is defined as the voltage at which a 10% increase in applied voltage increases the magnetizing current by 50%.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] For voltages greater than the knee point, the magnetizing current increases considerably even for small increments in voltage across the secondary terminals.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The knee-point voltage is less applicable for metering current transformers as their accuracy is generally much higher but constrained within a very small range of the current transformer rating, typically 1.2 to 1.5 times rated current.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] However, the concept of knee point voltage is very pertinent to protection current transformers, since they are necessarily exposed to fault currents of 20 to 30 times rated current.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Ideally, the primary and secondary currents of a current transformer should be in phase.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] In practice, this is impossible, but, at normal power frequencies, phase shifts of a few tenths of a degree are achievable, while simpler CTs may have larger phase shifts.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] For current measurement, phase shift is immaterial as ammeters only display the magnitude of the current.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] However, in wattmeters, energy meters, and power factor, phase shift produces errors.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] For power and energy measurement, the errors are considered to be negligible at unity power factor but become more significant as the power factor approaches zero.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The introduction of electronic power and energy meters has allowed current phase error to be calibrated out.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Bar-type current transformers have terminals for source and load connections of the primary circuit, and the body of the current transformer provides insulation between the primary circuit and ground.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] By use of oil insulation and porcelain bushings, such transformers can be applied at the highest transmission voltages.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Ring-type current transformers are installed over a bus bar or an insulated cable and have only a low level of insulation on the secondary coil.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] To obtain non-standard ratios or for other special purposes, more than one turn of the primary cable may be passed through the ring.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Where a metal shield is present in the cable jacket, it must be terminated so no net sheath current passes through the ring, to ensure accuracy.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers used to sense ground fault (zero sequence) currents, such as in a three-phase installation, may have three primary conductors passed through the ring.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Only the net unbalanced current produces a secondary current - this can be used to detect a fault from an energized conductor to ground.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Ring-type transformers usually use dry insulation systems, with a hard rubber or plastic case over the secondary windings.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] For temporary connections, a split ring-type current transformer can be slipped over a cable without disconnecting it.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] This type has a laminated iron core, with a hinged section that allows it to be installed over the cable; the core links the magnetic flux produced by the single turn primary winding to a wound secondary with many turns.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Because the gaps in the hinged segment introduce inaccuracy, such devices are not normally used for revenue metering.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers, especially those intended for high voltage substation service, may have multiple taps on their secondary windings, providing several ratios in the same device.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] This can be done to allow for reduced inventory of spare units, or to allow for load growth in an installation.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] A high-voltage current transformer may have several secondary windings with the same primary, to allow for separate metering and protection circuits, or for connection to different types of protective devices.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] For example, one secondary may be used for branch overcurrent protection, while a second winding may be used in a bus differential protective scheme, and a third winding used for power and current measurement.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Specially constructed *wideband current transformers* are also used (usually with an oscilloscope) to measure waveforms of high frequency or pulsed currents within pulsed power systems.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Unlike CTs used for power circuitry, wideband CTs are rated in output volts per ampere of primary current.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] If the burden resistance is much less than inductive impedance of the secondary winding at the measurement frequency then the current in the secondary tracks the primary current and the transformer provides a current output that is proportional to the measured current.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] On the other hand, if that condition is not true, then the transformer is inductive and gives a differential output.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The Rogowski coil uses this effect and requires an external integrator in order to provide a voltage output that is proportional to the measured current.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Ultimately, depending on client requirements, there are two main standards to which current transformers are designed.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] IEC 61869-1 (in the past IEC 60044-1) & IEEE C57.13 (ANSI), although the Canadian and Australian standards are also recognised.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers are used for protection, measurement and control in high-voltage electrical substations and the electrical grid.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Current transformers may be installed inside switchgear or in apparatus bushings, but very often free-standing outdoor current transformers are used.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] In a switchyard, *live tank* current transformers have a substantial part of their enclosure energized at the line voltage and must be mounted on insulators.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] *Dead tank* current transformers isolate the measured circuit from the enclosure.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Live tank CTs are useful because the primary conductor is short, which gives better stability and a higher short-circuit current rating.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] The primary of the winding can be evenly distributed around the magnetic core, which gives better performance for overloads and transients.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] Since the major insulation of a live-tank current transformer is not exposed to the heat of the primary conductors, insulation life and thermal stability is improved.
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] A high-voltage current transformer may contain several cores, each with a secondary winding, for different purposes (such as metering circuits, control, or protection).
[src:current-sensing/current-transformer] A neutral current transformer is used as earth fault protection to measure any fault current flowing through the neutral line from the wye neutral point of a transformer.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] A **Rogowski coil**, named after Walter Rogowski, is an electrical device for measuring alternating current (AC) or high-speed current pulses.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] It sometimes consists of a helical coil of wire with the lead from one end returning through the centre of the coil to the other end so that both terminals are at the same end of the coil.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] This approach is sometimes referred to as a *counter-wound* Rogowski.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] Other approaches use a full toroid geometry that has the advantage of a central excitation not exciting standing waves in the coil.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] The whole assembly is then wrapped around the straight conductor whose current is to be measured.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] The winding density, the diameter of the coil and the rigidity of the winding are critical for preserving immunity to external fields and low sensitivity to the positioning of the measured conductor.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] Single-chip signal processors with built-in analog to digital converters are often used for this purpose.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] If the ratio of the coil's inductance to its resistance (the RL time constant) is significantly greater than the length of the current pulse being measured, the coil is considered "self integrating".
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] When both ends of the coil are connected together, the current in the coil is proportional to the current being measured.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] Connecting the ends of the coil together through a low-value resistor allows the current to be measured by measuring the voltage drop over the resistor.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] Thus, the device produces an output voltage proportional to the current being measured.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] This type of coil has advantages over other types of current transformers.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] This type of coil also has some disadvantages over other types of current transformers.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] Rogowski coils are used for current monitoring in precision welding systems, arc melting furnaces, or electromagnetic launchers.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] They are also used in short-circuit testing of electric generators and as sensors in protection systems of electrical plants.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] Another field of usage is the measurement of harmonic current content, due to their high linearity.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] This formula assumes the turns are evenly spaced and that these turns are small relative to the radius of the coil itself.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] The output of the Rogowski coil is proportional to the derivative of the wire current.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] The output is often integrated so the output is proportional to the wire's current: $V_{\text{out}}=\int v\,dt={\frac {-AN\mu _{0}}{l}}I(t)+C_{\text{integration}}.$ In practice, an instrument will use a lossy integrator with a time constant much less than the lowest frequency of interest.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] The lossy integrator will reduce the effects of offset voltages and set the constant of integration to zero.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] At high frequencies, the Rogowski coil's inductance will decrease its output.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] A device similar to the Rogowski coil was described by Arthur Prince Chattock of Bristol University in 1887.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] Chattock used it to measure magnetic fields rather than currents.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] The definitive description was given by Walter Rogowski and W.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] More recently, low-cost current sensors based on the principle of a Rogowski coil have been developed.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] These sensors share the principles of a Rogowski coil, measuring the rate of change of current using a transformer with no magnetic core.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] The difference from the traditional Rogowski coil is that the sensor can be manufactured using a planar coil rather than a toroidal coil.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] In order to reject the influence of conductors outside the sensor's measurement region, these planar Rogowski current sensors use a concentric coil geometry instead of a toroidal geometry to limit the response to external fields.
[src:current-sensing/rogowski-coil] The main advantage of the planar Rogowski current sensor is that the coil winding precision that is a requirement for accuracy can be achieved using low-cost printed circuit board manufacturing.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] A **shunt** is a device designed to provide a low-impedance path for an electrical current in a circuit.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] It is typically used to divert current away from a system or component in order to prevent overcurrent.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Electrical shunts are used in a wide variety of applications including power distribution systems, electrical measurement systems, automotive and marine applications.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Shunts take many physical forms depending on their application.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] In current measurement, a shunt is a resistor of very low but precisely known resistance placed in parallel with a meter, allowing large currents to be measured indirectly via the voltage drop across it.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] In circuit protection, shunt devices such as crowbar circuits guard against overvoltage by short-circuiting the supply.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Capacitors are employed as shunts to redirect high-frequency electrical noise to ground.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] In photovoltaics, the term describes an unwanted short circuit within a solar cell, while in lightning protection, gas-filled tubes act as shunts to safely conduct surge energy to ground.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] On warships, battle short shunts are installed across fuses for essential equipment before entering combat.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] One example is in miniature Christmas lights which are wired in series.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] When the filament burns out in one of the incandescent light bulbs, the full line voltage appears across the burnt out bulb.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] A shunt resistor, which has been connected in parallel across the filament before it burnt out, will then short out to bypass the burnt filament and allow the rest of the string to light.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] If too many lights burn out however, a shunt will also burn out, requiring the use of a multimeter to find the point of failure.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] In photovoltaics, the term is widely used to describe an unwanted short circuit between the front and back surface contacts of a solar cell, usually caused by wafer damage.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] A gas-filled tube can also be used as a shunt, particularly in a lightning arrester.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Neon, like other noble gases, has a high breakdown voltage, so that normally current will not flow across it.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] However, a direct lightning strike (such as on a radio tower antenna) will cause the shunt to arc and conduct the massive amount of electricity to ground, protecting transmitters and other equipment.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Another older form of lightning arrester employs a simple narrow spark gap, over which an arc will jump when a high voltage is present.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] While a low cost solution, its high triggering voltage offers almost no protection for modern solid-state electronic devices powered by the protected circuit.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Capacitors are used as shunts to redirect high-frequency noise to ground before it can propagate to the load or other circuit components.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] The term shunt is used in filter and similar circuits with a ladder topology to refer to the components connected between the line and common.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] The term is used in this context to distinguish the shunt components connected between the signal and return lines from the components connected in series along the signal line.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] More generally, the term shunt can be used for a component connected in parallel with another.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] For instance, *shunt m-derived half section* is a common filter section from the image impedance method of filter design.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Where devices are vulnerable to reverse polarity of a signal or power supply, a diode may be used to protect the circuit.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] If connected in series with the circuit it simply prevents reversed current, but if connected in parallel it can shunt the reversed supply, causing a fuse or other current limiting circuit to open.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] All semiconductor diodes have a threshold voltage – typically between 0.5 volt and 1 volt – that must be exceeded before significant current will flow through the diode in the normally allowed direction.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Two anti-parallel shunt diodes (one to conduct current in each direction) can be used to limit the signal flowing past them to no more than their threshold voltages, in order to protect later components from overload.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] When a circuit must be protected from overvoltage and there are failure modes in the power supply that can produce such overvoltages, the circuit may be protected by a device commonly called a crowbar circuit.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] When this device detects an overvoltage it causes a short circuit between the power supply and its return.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] This will cause both an immediate drop in voltage (protecting the device) and an instantaneous high current which is expected to open a current sensitive device (such as a fuse or circuit breaker).
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] This device is called a *crowbar* as it is likened to dropping an actual crowbar across a set of bus bars (exposed electrical conductors).
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] On warships, it is common to install battle short shunts across fuses for essential equipment before entering combat.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] This bypasses overcurrent protection at a time when removing power to the equipment is not an appropriate reaction.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] This figure shows that the term "shunt resistor" should be understood in the context of what it shunts.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] In this example the resistor RL would be understood as "the shunt resistor" (to the load L), because this resistor would pass current around the load L.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] RL is connected in parallel with the load L.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] However, the series resistors RM1 and RM2 are low Ohmic resistors (like in the photo) meant to pass current around the instruments M1 and M2, and function as shunt resistors to those instruments.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] RM1 and RM2 are connected in parallel with M1 and M2.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] If seen without the instruments these two resistors would be considered series resistors in this circuit.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] An ammeter shunt allows the measurement of current values too large to be directly measured by a particular ammeter.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] The resistance is chosen so that the resultant voltage drop is measurable but low enough not to disrupt the circuit.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] The voltage across the shunt is proportional to the current flowing through it, and so the measured voltage can be scaled to directly display the current value.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Shunts are rated by maximum current and voltage drop at that current.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] For example, a 500 A, 75 mV shunt would have a resistance of 150 microohm, a maximum allowable current of 500 amps and at that current the voltage drop would be 75 millivolts.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] By convention, most shunts are designed to drop 50 mV, 75 mV or 100 mV when operating at their full rated current and most ammeters consist of a shunt and a voltmeter with full-scale deflections of 50, 75, or 100 mV.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] All shunts have a derating factor for continuous (more than 2 minutes) use, 66% being the most common, so the example shunt should not be operated above 330 A (and 50 mV drop) longer than that.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] This limitation is due to thermal limits at which a shunt will no longer operate correctly.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] If the current being measured is also at a high voltage potential this voltage will be present in the connecting leads too and in the reading instrument itself.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Sometimes, the shunt is inserted in the return leg (grounded side) to avoid this problem.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Some alternatives to shunts can provide isolation from the high voltage by not directly connecting the meter to the high voltage circuit.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Examples of devices that can provide this isolation are Hall effect current sensors and current transformers (see clamp meters).
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Current shunts are considered more accurate and cheaper than Hall effect devices.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Common accuracy specifications of such devices are ±0.1%, ±0.25% or ±0.5%.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] The Thomas-type double manganin walled shunt and MI type (improved Thomas-type design) were used by NIST and other standards laboratories as the legal reference of an ohm until superseded in 1990 by the quantum Hall effect.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Thomas-type shunts are still used as secondary standards to take very accurate current measurements, as using quantum Hall effect is a time-consuming process.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] The accuracy of these types of shunts is measured in the ppm and sub-ppm scale of drift per year of set resistance.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] Where the circuit is grounded (earthed) on one side, a current measuring shunt can be inserted either in the ungrounded conductor or in the grounded conductor.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] A shunt in the grounded conductor may not detect leakage current that bypasses the shunt, but it will not experience high common-mode voltage to ground.
[src:current-sensing/shunt-electrical] The load is removed from a direct path to ground, which may create problems for control circuitry, result in unwanted emissions, or both.
